spec: abc_extra159
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html — Python abc module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/abc.py"
    - "CPython source: Modules/_abc.c"
  notes:
    - "This spec covers: abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ attribute — its class name, emptiness, and module. abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__=='frozenset' (len=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9; the __abstractmethods__ attribute is always a frozenset in Python's ABC machinery); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__()==0 (ABC itself defines no @abstractmethod methods, so its __abstractmethods__ frozenset is empty); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__=='builtins' (frozenset is a builtin type); abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (established in extra158: __abstractmethods__ is stored directly in ABC.__dict__); abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==False (ABCMeta does NOT have __abstractmethods__ in its own __dict__ — ABCMeta is a metaclass, not a regular class with abstract methods). NOTE: abc.ABCMeta does not have an __abstractmethods__ attribute at all (hasattr(abc.ABCMeta, '__abstractmethods__')==False); the task description's mention of 'abc.ABCMeta.__abstractmethods__.__len__()==0' was corrected by live verification. All verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__=='frozenset' (len=9) — the type of __abstractmethods__ is always frozenset; Python's type machinery checks __abstractmethods__ at class instantiation and raises TypeError if it is a non-empty frozenset (meaning the class has unimplemented abstract methods); for abc.ABC itself, __abstractmethods__==frozenset() (empty) because ABC defines no @abstractmethod; the frozenset type is a builtin: frozenset.__module__=='builtins' (len=8: 'builtins'=8); frozenset.__name__=='frozenset' (len=9); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__()==9 ('frozenset'=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9). Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__()==0 — the empty frozenset indicates ABC has no abstract methods; a concrete class inheriting from ABC must implement all methods in __abstractmethods__ before it can be instantiated; if __abstractmethods__ is non-empty, Python raises TypeError: 'Can't instantiate abstract class X with abstract method(s) y, z'; for ABC.__abstractmethods__==frozenset() (empty), direct instantiation of ABC() would succeed (but is unusual); contrast: any abstract class with @abstractmethod decorated methods would have a non-empty __abstractmethods__. Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==False — ABCMeta, being a metaclass (subclass of type), does not store __abstractmethods__ in its own __dict__; the __abstractmethods__ attribute is a characteristic of classes whose metaclass is ABCMeta; ABCMeta itself, as a type/metaclass subclass, is not subject to the ABCMeta.__abstractmethods__ protocol in the same way; hasattr(abc.ABCMeta, '__abstractmethods__')==False confirms this. Additionally, type.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (the base type metaclass has __abstractmethods__ in its dict, which is where the slot for this attribute is defined). Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ class name and emptiness — extra159
#
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('frozenset')  == True
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__()                               == 0
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__()            == 9
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__eq__('builtins') == True
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table abc_extra159.abc_abstractmethods_class_identity:
  description: "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ class name and emptiness checks in abcabsm159 namespace — abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('frozenset')==True (__abstractmethods__ is always a frozenset; the frozenset type is used because it is immutable — the abstract method set for a class does not change after class creation; 'frozenset' len=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__()==0 (ABC itself defines no @abstractmethod methods so its __abstractmethods__ is the empty frozenset; empty means ABC can be instantiated directly and subclasses of ABC without @abstractmethod are immediately concrete); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__()==9 ('frozenset'=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9; the class name length is 9); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__eq__('builtins')==True (frozenset is a builtin type defined in the CPython core, not in any Python module; __module__=='builtins' len=8: 'builtins'=8); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: abcabsm159

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [absm_class_name_eq,   abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__,    ["frozenset"],  true,  "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__ == 'frozenset' (frozenset is immutable set used for abstract methods); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [absm_len_zero,        abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__,                       [],             0,     "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__() == 0 (ABC has no @abstractmethod; empty frozenset); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [absm_class_name_len,  abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__,   [],             9,     "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__() == 9 ('frozenset'=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [absm_class_mod_eq,    abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__eq__,  ["builtins"],   true,  "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__ == 'builtins' (frozenset is a builtin type); verified with Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# abc.ABC.__dict__ and abc.ABCMeta.__dict__ for __abstractmethods__ — extra159
#
# abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')     == True
# abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__') == False
# type.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')        == True
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table abc_extra159.abc_abstractmethods_dict_membership:
  description: "abc.ABC and abc.ABCMeta __dict__ membership for __abstractmethods__ in abcabsmdict159 namespace — abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (established in extra158; '__abstractmethods__' is stored directly in abc.ABC.__dict__ as a frozenset(); each class using ABCMeta gets its own __abstractmethods__ stored in its own __dict__; for ABC itself the value is frozenset() because ABC defines no abstract methods); abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==False (KEY FINDING: ABCMeta does NOT have __abstractmethods__ in its own __dict__; ABCMeta is a metaclass — its instances are classes, not objects; the ABCMeta machinery sets __abstractmethods__ on classes it creates, but ABCMeta itself does not have this attribute; hasattr(abc.ABCMeta, '__abstractmethods__')==False in Python 3.14.3); type.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (the built-in type metaclass has '__abstractmethods__' in its dict — this is the slot descriptor that enables the attribute on all classes; ABCMeta inherits from type, and type defines the __abstractmethods__ slot); abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__slots__')==True (also established in extra158); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: abcabsmdict159

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [abc_dict_has_absm,   abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__,     ["__abstractmethods__"],  true,   "ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__') == True (frozenset() stored directly in ABC.__dict__); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [meta_dict_no_absm,   abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__,  ["__abstractmethods__"],  false,  "ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__') == False (ABCMeta is a metaclass; does not have this attr); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [type_dict_has_absm,  type.__dict__.__contains__,         ["__abstractmethods__"],  true,   "type.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__') == True (type defines the __abstractmethods__ slot); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [abc_dict_has_slots,  abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__,     ["__slots__"],             true,   "ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__slots__') == True (established in extra158; ABC defines __slots__=()); verified with Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ membership and type checks — extra159
#
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('frozenset')  == True
# abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__('object') == True
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table abc_extra159.abc_abstractmethods_type_checks:
  description: "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ type cross-checks in abcabsmtype159 namespace — abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('frozenset')==True (cross-check of the frozenset class name; 'frozenset'=9 chars); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__()==9 (len of 'frozenset'=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9; note: 'frozenset'=9 > 'set'=3 by 6 chars — the 'frozen'=6 prefix doubles the name length relative to 'set'); abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__len__()==8 ('builtins'=8: 'b'+'u'+'i'+'l'+'t'+'i'+'n'+'s'=8; the builtins module name is 8 chars); abc.ABC.__name__.__len__()==3 (abc.ABC.__name__=='ABC' len=3; cross-reference established in prior specs: ABC(3) < ABCMeta(7) in name length; shorter than 'frozenset'=9 by 6); abc.ABC.__module__.__len__()==3 ('abc'=3; same short length as ABC.__name__=3; 'abc'=3 is the module name length); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: abcabsmtype159

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [absm_class_name_eq2,  abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__,     ["frozenset"],  true,  "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__ == 'frozenset' (type is frozenset; cross-check); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [absm_class_name_len2, abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__,    [],             9,     "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__len__() == 9 ('frozenset'=9; 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [absm_class_mod_len,   abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__len__,  [],             8,     "ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__len__() == 8 ('builtins'=8); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [abc_name_len,         abc.ABC.__name__.__len__,                                  [],             3,     "abc.ABC.__name__.__len__() == 3 ('ABC'=3; same as 'abc' module name length); verified with Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Standalone invariants — extra159
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant abc_extra159.abc_ABC_abstractmethods_class_name_eq:
  description: "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('frozenset') returns True — abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ is an instance of frozenset; the __abstractmethods__ attribute on any class with ABCMeta as its metaclass is always a frozenset; Python's type machinery requires __abstractmethods__ to be a frozenset (or set-like) containing the names of abstract methods; frozenset is chosen because the abstract method set of a class is immutable after class creation — it cannot be modified at runtime (without metaclass trickery); for abc.ABC itself, __abstractmethods__==frozenset() (the empty frozenset); frozenset.__name__=='frozenset' (len=9: 'frozen'=6+'set'=3=9); frozenset.__module__=='builtins' (frozenset is a builtin type); compare: abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (established in extra158: the frozenset() is stored directly in ABC.__dict__); NEW in extra159: first standalone ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__ invariant in abcabsm159 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["frozenset"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra159.abc_ABC_abstractmethods_len_zero:
  description: "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__() returns 0 — abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__ is an empty frozenset; len==0 means ABC has no abstract methods that must be implemented by subclasses; abc.ABC is the helper class for defining ABCs — it has no @abstractmethod decorated methods of its own; contrast: if a class defines @abstractmethod methods, its __abstractmethods__.__len__() is non-zero and attempting to instantiate that class raises TypeError; abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__()==0 confirms ABC is not itself abstract in the 'must implement methods' sense; any class that inherits from abc.ABC but does not define @abstractmethod will also have __abstractmethods__.__len__()==0 and can be instantiated freely; compare: abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__=='frozenset' (type is frozenset; established in the table above); abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (the frozenset() is in ABC.__dict__; established in extra158); NEW in extra159: first standalone ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__ invariant in abcabsm159 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__len__
  args: []
  expected: 0

invariant abc_extra159.abc_ABC_dict_has_abstractmethods:
  description: "abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__') returns True — established in extra158 and confirmed again here in the abc_extra159 context; '__abstractmethods__' is stored directly in abc.ABC.__dict__ as frozenset(); the presence of '__abstractmethods__' in ABC.__dict__ means the attribute is directly on ABC rather than inherited; each class using ABCMeta as its metaclass gets its own __abstractmethods__ frozenset in its own __dict__; when ABCMeta creates a new class, it computes the new class's __abstractmethods__ by collecting all @abstractmethod decorated methods from the class body and all inherited abstract methods not overridden; for ABC itself (which defines no @abstractmethod), the result is frozenset(); abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==False (ABCMeta itself does not have this attr in its dict — only classes managed by ABCMeta have it); compare: type.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (the slot descriptor for __abstractmethods__ is defined on type); verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__
  args: ["__abstractmethods__"]
  expected: true

invariant abc_extra159.abc_ABCMeta_dict_no_abstractmethods:
  description: "abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__') returns False — ABCMeta does NOT have '__abstractmethods__' in its own __dict__; this is a KEY FINDING: ABCMeta is a metaclass (a subclass of type) and is not subject to the ABCMeta abstract method tracking protocol in the same way regular classes are; hasattr(abc.ABCMeta, '__abstractmethods__') evaluates to False in Python 3.14.3, confirming the attribute is completely absent; abc.ABC.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (ABC, a regular class, has __abstractmethods__ directly in its dict) while abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==False (ABCMeta, the metaclass, does not); type.__dict__.__contains__('__abstractmethods__')==True (the descriptor for the attribute is defined on type, not ABCMeta); this clarifies that __abstractmethods__ is a class attribute of ordinary classes, managed by the type protocol through ABCMeta, but ABCMeta itself does not use the attribute for itself; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: abc.ABCMeta.__dict__.__contains__
  args: ["__abstractmethods__"]
  expected: false

invariant abc_extra159.abc_ABC_abstractmethods_class_module_eq:
  description: "abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__eq__('builtins') returns True — the frozenset class (which is the type of __abstractmethods__) has __module__=='builtins' (len=8: 'b'+'u'+'i'+'l'+'t'+'i'+'n'+'s'=8); frozenset is a built-in type implemented in CPython's core (Objects/setobject.c) and exposed in the builtins module; compare module lengths: 'builtins'=8 > 'abc'=3 (the abc module name is much shorter than 'builtins'); 'builtins'=8 < 'asyncio.locks'=13 (the builtins module name is shorter than asyncio submodule paths); the frozenset type is one of Python's fundamental immutable collection types alongside tuple and frozenset; abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__name__=='frozenset' (len=9; the class name is 1 char longer than its module name 'builtins'=8... wait: 'frozenset'=9 > 'builtins'=8 by 1 char); NEW in extra159: first standalone ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__ invariant in abcabsm159 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: abc.ABC.__abstractmethods__.__class__.__module__.__eq__
  args: ["builtins"]
  expected: true

